102','','Fluoroquinolones inhibit type II and type IV topoisomerases (2 strand breaking enzymes) such as GyrA/GyrB and ParC/ParE. Point mutations in the associated gyrA and parC genes, in particular in the `quinolone resistance determining region` (QRDR), give rise to resistance to the class.'),(386,'ARO:3000453','streptogramin vat acetyltransferase','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000233','confers_resistance_to ARO:0000026,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000669,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000672,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000673,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000674,participates_in ARO:3000106','vat (Virginiamycin acetyltransferases) enzymes catalyze the transfer of an acetyl group from acetyl-CoA to the secondary alcohol of streptogramin A compounds, thus inactivating virginiamycin-like antibiotics and conferring resistance to these compounds.'),(387,'ARO:3000454','polymyxin B','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:0000022,ARO:3000707','','Polymyxin B is mixture of mostly polymyxins B1 and B2, mainly used for resistant gram-negative infections. They are polypeptides with cationic detergent action on cell membranes.'),(388,'ARO:3000455','streptogramin A biosynthesis','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000388','','Type A streptogramins are produced by a hybrid NRPS/PKS composed of 8 NRPS modules and 2 PKS modules.'),(389,'ARO:3000456','thiamphenicol','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000387','','Derivative of Chloramphenicol. The nitro group (-NO2) is substituted by a sulfomethyl group (-SO2CH3).'),(390,'ARO:3000457','aminocoumarin resistant parE','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000115,ARO:3000477','confers_resistance_to ARO:3000103,derives_from ARO:3000023','ParE is a subunit of topoisomerase IV, which decatenates and relaxes DNA to allow access to genes for transcription or translation. Point mutations in ParE prevent anticoumarin antibiotics from inhibiting DNA synthesis, thus conferring resistance.'),(391,'ARO:3000458','macrolide glycosyltransferase','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000201','participates_in ARO:3000208','Macrolide glycosyltransferases are enzymes encoded by macrolide glycosyltransferase genes and inactivate macrolides by glycosylating them at 2`-OH of desosamine sugar moiety. They are predominantly found in macrolide producers and are also found in non-producers and are used as a resistance mechanism. Different variants of this enzyme has been reported.'),(392,'ARO:3000459','fosfomycin biosynthesis','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000082','','Biosynthesis of fosfomycin.'),(393,'ARO:3000461','florfenicol','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000387','','Florfenicol is a fluorine derivative of chloramphenicol, where the nitro group (-NO2) is substituted by a sulfomethyl group (-SO2CH3) and the hydroxyl group (-OH), by a fluorine group (-F). The action mechanism is the same as chloramphenicol`s, where the antibiotic binds to the 23S RNA of the 50S subunit of bacterial ribosomes to inhibit protein synthesis.'),(394,'ARO:3000462','mgtA','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3004237','confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000006,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000145,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000158,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3001232','A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the mgtA gene in Streptomyces lividans. This enzyme inactivates macrolides using UDP-glucose as a cofactor. Its optimal substrates are lankamycin, calcomycin, rosaramicin, methymycin, and pikromycin, while interactions with erythomycin, oldeandomycin, azithromycin, and tylosin were weaker. It is inactive against spiramycin and carbomycin. Mechanism first described by Cundliffe, 1992.'),(395,'ARO:3000463','gimA','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3004236','confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000145,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3000867,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3001222,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3001232','A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the gimA gene in Streptomyces ambofaciens, a natural producer of the macrolide antibiotic spiramycin. Chalcomycin, methymycin, tylosin, pikromycin, rosaramicin, oleandomycin, josamycin, and carbomycin are preferred substrates of gimA glycosyltransferase, while erythromycin and spiramycin have notably low binding affinities. GimA may be able to inactivate spiramycin precursors. Described by Gourmelen et al. 1998.'),(396,'ARO:3000464','Neisseria gonorrhoeae porin PIB (por)','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000472,ARO:3004281','confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000051','Mutant forms of the porin Por result in reduced permeability to antibiotics, particularly tetracyclines and beta-lactams.'),(397,'ARO:3000465','ole glycosyltransferase','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000458','confers_resistance_to ARO:0000000','OleI and OleD are glycosyltransferases found in Streptomyces antibioticus which is a natural producer of antibiotic oleandomycin. OleI glycosylates antibiotic oleandomycin whereas OleD can glycosylate a wide variety of macrolides.'),(398,'ARO:3000466','dalbavancin','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000081','','Dalbavancin is a semisynthetic second-generation lipoglycopeptide derived from teicoplanin. It binds to the D-Ala-D-Ala terminus of peptidoglycan precursors. It is used to treat Gram-positive bacteria and can be used to treat methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus and vancomycin-resistant enterococci.'),(399,'ARO:3000467','NDM-5','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000057','confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000008,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000060,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000070,confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:3004021','New Delhi beta-lactamase NDM-5.'),(400,'ARO:3000469','hydroxypropylphosphonic acid epoxidase','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000459','','The enzyme responsible for the final step of fosfomycin biosynthesis. It converts S-2-hydroxypropylphosphonic acid (S-HPP) into fosfomycin via an oxidative cyclalization reaction. It uses Iron (II) or Zinc (II) as cofactors.'),(401,'ARO:3000472','determinant of tetracycline resistance','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000000','confers_resistance_to ARO:3000050','Enzymes, other proteins or other gene products shown clinically to confer resistance to tetracycline antibiotics or tetracycline-like derivatives.'),(402,'ARO:3000476','tet(31)','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:0010002','confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000051','Tet31 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Aeromonas salmonicida, a Gram-negative bacteria. It has also been shown to be expressed in Gallibacterium anatis.'),(403,'ARO:3000477','determinant of aminocoumarin resistance','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000000','confers_resistance_to ARO:3000103','Point mutations to DNA topoisomerase enzymes clinically shown to confer resistance to aminocoumarins. In some cases, expression of parY(R), which encodes an aminocoumarin resistant topoisomerase IV, can also confer aminocoumarin resistance.'),(404,'ARO:3000478','tet(33)','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:0010002','confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000051','Tet33 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Gram-positive bacteria, including Arthrobacter and Corynebacterium.'),(405,'ARO:3000479','aminocoumarin resistant gyrB','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000220,ARO:3000477','confers_resistance_to ARO:3000103,derives_from ARO:3003260','Point mutations in DNA gyrase subunit B (gyrB) can result in resistance to aminocoumarins. These mutations usually involve arginine residues in organisms.'),(406,'ARO:3000480','aminocoumarin resistant parY','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000209,ARO:3000477','confers_resistance_to ARO:3000103,derives_from ARO:3003253','Expression of parY(R), which encodes an aminocoumarin resistant topoisomerase IV, can confer aminocoumarin resistance.'),(407,'ARO:3000481','tet(35)','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:0010001','confers_resistance_to_drug ARO:0000051','Tet35 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in the Gram-negative Vibrio and Stenotrophomonas. It is unrelated to other tet resistance genes.'),(408,'ARO:3000488','telavancin','antibiotic_resistance','ARO:3000081','','Telavancin is a semi-